"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773011","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-01","<p>Any taxi, private hire car, self-employed driver (including Uber drivers) or any other type of taxi or private hire vehicle where the annual taxable turnover exceeds £85,000 must register and charge VAT on their supplies.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-11-01T12:49:38.733Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773011/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773011/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773011/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Taxis: VAT","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether (1) taxis, (2) private hire cars, (3) Uber drivers, and (4) other types of taxi and private hire vehicle, are subject to VAT; and, if not, why not.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL2212"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773012","Department for Education","false","2017-11-01","<p>The Terms and Conditions of Lord Shinkwin’s appointment as an Equality and Human Rights Commission (EHRC) Commissioner are the same as those of other EHRC Board members.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2017-11-01T17:42:29.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773012/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773012/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773012/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-18","Equality and Human Rights Commission","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the answer by Baroness Vere of Norbiton on 16 October (HL Deb, cols 393–5), what are the terms of the agreement between the Chair of the Equality and Human Rights Commission and Lord Shinkwin regarding his participation in the Commission's work.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL2213"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773013","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>The new scheme was put in place to ensure that refugees who wish to apply for benefits are assisted with their application and receive a prompt first payment of any benefit for which they qualify. The scheme was tested successfully in the North East and Yorkshire and Humberside regions earlier this year and has now been rolled out to all areas of the country where asylum seekers are accommodated by the Home Office.</p><p>We are talking to the main voluntary sector groups representing refugees about the roll put process and providing information about how the scheme works.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-01T13:37:27.32Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773013/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773013/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773013/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-18","Refugees: Social Security Benefits","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Williams of Trafford on 25 July 2016 (HL1295), when they expect to publish their evaluation of the pilot scheme, carried out by the Home Office and the Department for Work and Pensions, to expedite the first payment of any benefit for which newly recognised refugees qualify.","false","Biography information for Baroness Lister of Burtersett",,"Baroness Lister of Burtersett","HL2214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773014","Department for Education","false","2017-10-31","<p>All children regardless of their circumstances are entitled to a good education and the necessary support to attain it.</p><p> </p><p>Schools have a duty to ensure that arrangements are made to support pupils with medical needs to have full access to education. Where health needs mean a child of compulsory school age would not receive suitable education due to health needs, including because they cannot attend school, local councils have a duty to ensure that alternative education arrangements are put in place.</p><p>The education must be full time, or as close to full time as in the best interests of the child, because of their health needs, and it must be on par with what the child would have received if they were in a mainstream school.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2017-10-31T17:27:04.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773014/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773014/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773014/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-18","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the provision of, and access to, educational materials for girls whose education has been disrupted due to symptoms developed after human papilloma virus vaccination.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL2215"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773015","Department of Health","false","2017-10-31","<p>As with all vaccines and medicines, the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency (MHRA) closely monitors the safety of the human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine. The MHRA takes advice from the Government's independent expert advisory body, the Commission on Human Medicines (CHM), when evaluating the risks and benefits of medicines and vaccines.</p><p> </p><p>The MHRA takes account of all available sources of safety data, including reports of suspected side effects submitted through the Yellow Card Scheme. A Yellow Card report is not proof of a side effect occurring, but a suspicion by the reporter that the vaccine may have been the cause. Such reports are kept under continual review.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2008, at least three million girls have been vaccinated with HPV vaccine across the United Kingdom. Through the Yellow Card Scheme, 341 reports included a suspected psychiatric event. The detailed medical history is not always provided in Yellow Card reports. Evaluation of such reports does not indicate a causal association with the HPV vaccine. In July 2015, the CHM thoroughly reviewed the safety of HPV vaccines and concluded that the evidence does not support a link between HPV vaccination and the development of chronic illnesses.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-10-31T12:34:43.117Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773015/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773015/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773015/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-18","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the number of girls diagnosed with mental health problems shortly after human papilloma virus vaccination, particularly when there has been no record of previous mental health disorder or serious health issues prior to vaccination.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL2216"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773016","Department of Health","false","2017-10-31","<p>Current evidence from clinical trials has demonstrated that protection against targeted human papilloma virus types following vaccination using Cervarix lasts for at least nine years and at least eight years for Gardasil. The immunological evidence supports expectations that these vaccines will protect for much longer.</p><p> </p><p>The duration of protection for Gardasil 9 is not yet known.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-10-31T12:35:08.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773016/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773016/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773016/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-18","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government for how long the three vaccination regime for human papilloma virus, in the form of Gardasil, Gardasil 9 or Cervarix, maintains protection against infection.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL2217"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773017","Department of Health","false","2017-10-31","<p>Chronic Fatigue Syndrome (CFS) is a condition that occurs naturally in the age group eligible for human papillomavirus (HPV) vaccine. The Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency has completed a United Kingdom epidemiological study which found no evidence to suggest that HPV vaccine may increase the risk of developing CFS. The results of this study were published in a peer-reviewed scientific journal in 2013.</p><p> </p><p>This finding is further supported by the results of a recent population-based study in Norway, which similarly found no evidence of a causal association between HPV vaccine and CFS. Copies of HPV vaccination and risk of chronic fatigue syndrome/myalgic encephalomyelitis: A nationwide register-based study from Norway and Bivalent human papillomavirus vaccine and the risk of fatigue syndromes in girls in the UK are attached.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-10-31T12:39:52.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773017/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773017/answer","HPV CFS Norway study.pdf ; MHRA CPRD study HPV and CFS.pdf","HPV CFS Norway study.pdf ; MHRA CPRD study HPV and CFS.pdf","HPV vaccination Norway study ; HPV vaccination: girls in the UK","HPV vaccination Norway study ; HPV vaccination: girls in the UK","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773017/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-18","Human Papillomavirus: Vaccination","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the Department of Health recognises Chronic Fatigue Syndrome which develops up to six months after vaccination with human papilloma virus vaccine as a symptom of an adverse reaction to the vaccine.","false","Biography information for The Countess of Mar",,"The Countess of Mar","HL2218"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773018","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-08","<p>The British Consulate General Los Angeles did not employ external consultants specifically to work on any of the events mentioned by the Noble Lord.</p><p>The Department for International Trade has used agency support in some our work to promote the UK’s excellent creative industries globally, often delivering through partnerships with organisations such as with Variety, BFI, BFC and BAFTA.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead",,"2017-11-08T13:47:11.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773018/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773018/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773018/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-18","Trade Promotion: USA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much was spent by the British Consulate General Los Angeles' office on external consultants during the Golden Globe Awards 2017, Grammy Awards 2017 and Academy Awards 2017; what were the objectives set for such expenditure; and what assessment was made of the performance of external consultants against those objectives.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2219"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773019","Department of Health","false","2017-11-01","<p>The United Kingdom Government considers international inter-governmental co-operation to be essential in the development of new antibiotics.</p><p>Through international forums, in particular the G20, the UK Government is advocating tangible actions that will incentivise pharmaceutical companies to produce effective, accessible and affordable new antibiotics. The Government is also investing internationally in early-stage research and development to address antimicrobial resistance, in partnership with other countries and organisations, through projects such as the Global Anti-Microbial Resistance Innovation Fund.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-11-01T16:05:22.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773019/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773019/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773019/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-18","Antibiotics: Research","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their policy on international intergovernmental co-operation to offset market failures in the development of new antibiotics.","false","Biography information for Lord Moonie",,"Lord Moonie","HL2220"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773020","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2017-10-23","<p>Alongside our negotiations with the European Commission on the UK's exit from the European Union, the Government has regular and extensive engagement with EU Member States. These discussions lay the groundwork for constructive dialogue as we seek a successful outcome with the European Union.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2017-10-23T11:47:29.437Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773020/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773020/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773020/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2017-10-18","Customs","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to EU member states regarding the cost of new customs facilities and infrastructure that would be required in the event of a no deal outcome from the Brexit negotiations.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2221"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773021","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-01","<p>The costs of repatriating Monarch’s ATOL protected customers will be met by the ATOL scheme. The costs of repatriating all other passengers will be met by Her Majesty’s Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Civil Aviation Authority has estimated the total repatriation costs to be approximately £60m, although some of these costs will be met by the ATOL scheme. Government is also seeking to recover costs through credit card companies and travel providers who would otherwise be liable. HM Treasury has not made its own assessment of the costs and do not produce forecasts of future tax payments by specific taxpayers.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2223 ; HL2288","2017-11-01T12:49:21.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773021/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773021/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773021/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Monarch Airlines: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the amount of tax income and public revenue that will be foregone as a result of the failure of Monarch Airlines.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2222"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773022","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-01","<p>The costs of repatriating Monarch’s ATOL protected customers will be met by the ATOL scheme. The costs of repatriating all other passengers will be met by Her Majesty’s Government.</p><p> </p><p>The Civil Aviation Authority has estimated the total repatriation costs to be approximately £60m, although some of these costs will be met by the ATOL scheme. Government is also seeking to recover costs through credit card companies and travel providers who would otherwise be liable. HM Treasury has not made its own assessment of the costs and do not produce forecasts of future tax payments by specific taxpayers.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2222 ; HL2288","2017-11-01T12:49:21.343Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773022/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773022/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773022/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Monarch Airlines: Insolvency","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the costs of repatriating customers of Monarch Airlines to the UK will be met, in any part, by HM Treasury; and if so, what assessment they have made of such costs.","false","Biography information for Lord Myners",,"Lord Myners","HL2223"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773023","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-01","<p>The government is continuing to study the draft implementing legislation for Articles 15 and 16 of the EU Tobacco Products Directive and is discussing the drafts with the Commission and other Member States. We are aware of concerns raised by businesses affected and are working to try to ensure that the system adopted is effective, efficient and proportionate in tackling the trade in illicit tobacco products which puts public health at risk and avoids the payment of duty.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to assess the impact of the legislation and the timetable for implementation as the drafts develop, and we welcome and encourage those affected to continue to contribute their views and concerns.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2225 ; HL2226","2017-11-01T12:50:11.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773023/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773023/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773023/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Tobacco: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the potential impact on business resulting from the implementation, in their current form, of Articles 15 and 16 of the EU Tobacco Products Directive.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL2224"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773024","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-01","<p>The government is continuing to study the draft implementing legislation for Articles 15 and 16 of the EU Tobacco Products Directive and is discussing the drafts with the Commission and other Member States. We are aware of concerns raised by businesses affected and are working to try to ensure that the system adopted is effective, efficient and proportionate in tackling the trade in illicit tobacco products which puts public health at risk and avoids the payment of duty.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to assess the impact of the legislation and the timetable for implementation as the drafts develop, and we welcome and encourage those affected to continue to contribute their views and concerns.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2224 ; HL2226","2017-11-01T12:50:11.977Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773024/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773024/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773024/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Tobacco: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they plan to pause implementation of Articles 15 and 16 of the EU Tobacco Products Directive in the light of concerns raised by UK business, and in the light of Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL2225"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773025","HM Treasury","false","2017-11-01","<p>The government is continuing to study the draft implementing legislation for Articles 15 and 16 of the EU Tobacco Products Directive and is discussing the drafts with the Commission and other Member States. We are aware of concerns raised by businesses affected and are working to try to ensure that the system adopted is effective, efficient and proportionate in tackling the trade in illicit tobacco products which puts public health at risk and avoids the payment of duty.</p><p> </p><p>We will continue to assess the impact of the legislation and the timetable for implementation as the drafts develop, and we welcome and encourage those affected to continue to contribute their views and concerns.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2224 ; HL2225","2017-11-01T12:50:12.04Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773025/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773025/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773025/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Tobacco: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the extent to which current proposals for implementation of Articles 15 and 16 of the EU Tobacco Products Directive, as consulted upon by the European Commission, go beyond the original intent of the Directive; and whether they support the implementation of such measures.","false","Biography information for Lord Palmer",,"Lord Palmer","HL2226"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773026","Department of Health","false","2017-11-01","<p>No such discussions are currently planned.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-11-01T12:48:04.753Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773026/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773026/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773026/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-18","Neural Tube Defects","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what consideration they have given to holding a discussion with the governments of Denmark, the Netherlands, France, Poland and Germany, and the governments of the United States and Canada, on the difference in rates of neural tube defects in live births in those two groups of countries in order to explore the different policies which may have led to such differences.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2227"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773027","Department of Health","false","2017-10-31","<p>No assessment has been made of the effectiveness of advice given to women of child bearing age planning a pregnancy according to socio-economic group, ethnicity, and regional location.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2017-10-31T15:07:06.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773027/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773027/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773027/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-10-18","Pregnancy: Health Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they measure the effectiveness of advice given to women of child bearing age planning a pregnancy according to (1) socio-economic group, (2) ethnicity, and (3) regional location, and if so, how.","false","Biography information for Lord Rooker",,"Lord Rooker","HL2228"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773028","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-31","<p>The Government’s published response to this consultation indicates that the Government will consider further what measures, if any, are needed. The outcome of that decision will be announced in due course.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2017-10-31T12:47:09.937Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773028/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773028/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773028/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-18","Mileometers: Fraud","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether their recent response to the consultation on vehicle clocking means that no further action will be taken, or whether it means that consideration is being given to further action in the light of the responses to the consultation; and if it is the latter, whether the outcome of that consideration wil be announced before the end of 2017.","false","Biography information for Lord Rosser",,"Lord Rosser","HL2229"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773029","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-02","<p>In 2015 UK Trade &amp; Investment (UKTI) considered the development track record and market capital of Sichuan Guodong Construction Group Corporation Limited, the parent company, and Sichuan Guodong Construction Ltd, a listed subsidiary company on the Shanghai Stock Exchange, in relation to their ability to make significant investments in Sheffield. This included a recommendation from the Ministry of Commerce of the People's Republic of China that Wang Chunming, chairman of both companies, was included in the business delegation alongside President Xi for his October 2015 State Visit to the UK.</p><p>This consideration of this group of companies was in conjunction with UKTI taking a role in supporting the relationship that had emerged between this group of companies and Sheffield City Council.</p><p>On 28<sup>th</sup> June 2016 a co-operation signing document was signed between Sichuan Guodong Construction Group Corporation Ltd (the parent company) and Sheffield City Council.</p><p>In 2015 UKTI did not identify undue risks when considering whether they should take a role in supporting the relationship that had emerged between the Sichuan Guodong group of companies and Sheffield City Council. Therefore no risks were identified to Sheffield City Council.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead","HL2231","2017-11-02T16:10:28.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773029/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773029/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773029/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-18","Sichuan Guodong Construction Group: Sheffield","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the Sichuan Guodong Construction Group in relationship to the Sheffield City Council investment deal with that Group.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2230"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773030","Department for International Trade","false","2017-11-02","<p>In 2015 UK Trade &amp; Investment (UKTI) considered the development track record and market capital of Sichuan Guodong Construction Group Corporation Limited, the parent company, and Sichuan Guodong Construction Ltd, a listed subsidiary company on the Shanghai Stock Exchange, in relation to their ability to make significant investments in Sheffield. This included a recommendation from the Ministry of Commerce of the People's Republic of China that Wang Chunming, chairman of both companies, was included in the business delegation alongside President Xi for his October 2015 State Visit to the UK.</p><p>This consideration of this group of companies was in conjunction with UKTI taking a role in supporting the relationship that had emerged between this group of companies and Sheffield City Council.</p><p>On 28<sup>th</sup> June 2016 a co-operation signing document was signed between Sichuan Guodong Construction Group Corporation Ltd (the parent company) and Sheffield City Council.</p><p>In 2015 UKTI did not identify undue risks when considering whether they should take a role in supporting the relationship that had emerged between the Sichuan Guodong group of companies and Sheffield City Council. Therefore no risks were identified to Sheffield City Council.</p>",,"Baroness Fairhead","HL2230","2017-11-02T16:10:28.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773030/answer","Biography information for Baroness Fairhead","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773030/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773030/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2017-10-18","Sichuan Guodong Construction Group: Sheffield","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what risks they highlighted in their due diligence on the Sichuan Guodong Construction Group; and what information about those risks they then passed on to Sheffield City Council in the light of their investment deal with that Group.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773031","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>Border Force does not hold the data requested.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-01T12:54:55.667Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773031/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773031/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773031/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-18","Immigration Controls","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how many passports did not work at ePassport gates in airports in the UK in (1) 2014, (2) 2015, and (3) 2016.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2232"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773032","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>Two Government departments have involvement with this type of technology.</p><p>The Home Office operates the e-gates facial recognition system at some airports. This compares a person’s face with biometric information held in their passport. The purpose of this system is to verify identity and speed entry to the UK by reducing the need for people to pass through desks staffed by immigration officers.</p><p>The Home Office also operates the Police National Database on behalf of police forces. This includes a database of facial images taken from people who have been arrested. Images of suspects can be compared with this database for the purpose of detection of crime.</p><p>The Department for Transport regulates Eurotunnel’s use of biometric checks on staff entry to high security zones but it does not use facial biometric technology to run checks on members of the public.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-11-01T16:59:45.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773032/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773032/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773032/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Government Departments: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government which Government departments are using facial biometric technology; and for what reasons and purposes.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2233"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773033","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2017-10-31","<p>If the leaders of the Sheffield City Region do not at some stage undertake the consultation, they will have chosen to walk away from the deal denying the people of the City Region some £1 billion investment from Government and the opportunity for the area to have new powers on transport, development, and skills. But as the Government has made clear, we remain committed to the deal and the mayoral election on 3 May 2018 for which Parliament has legislated. Even without devolved powers and budgets the election of such a mayor is not without benefits for the City Region, since the elected mayor would be a significant figure who would both be chair of the combined authority and could take their place as the voice of the city region alongside the other city region mayors in the Northern Powerhouse and in other forums with Government or stakeholders.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2017-10-31T14:47:11.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773033/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773033/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773033/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2017-10-18","City Region Deals: Sheffield","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, if the proposed consultation on the Sheffield City Region deal does not proceed, what alternative steps they will take to proceed with the devolution agreement.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2234"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773034","Home Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>The information requested is not held centrally.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2017-11-01T13:36:35.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773034/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773034/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773034/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-18","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the number of facial biometric recognition systems currently being used by police forces in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL2235"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773035","Department for Education","false","2017-10-30","<p>My Rt hon. Friend, the Secretary of State has confirmed that we will publish a careers strategy shortly.</p><p>The strategy will have a clear focus on social mobility. It will include proposals to improve the quality and coverage of careers advice in schools. The strategy will also include steps to improve the access to advice on training and careers for adults throughout their working lives.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2017-10-30T17:26:20.627Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773035/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773035/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773035/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-18","Vocational Guidance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government when they intend to publish the comprehensive careers strategy announced in the Building the Industrial Strategy Green Paper, published in January.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL2236"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773036","Department for Education","false","2017-10-30","<p>The Government will publish a careers strategy shortly, with a clear focus on social mobility. This will include proposals to provide information for individuals to access education and training throughout their working lives, as well as help those who want to reskill and upskill.</p><p> </p><p>The National Careers Service provides free and impartial guidance on careers, skills and the Labour Market in England. It allows working people to identify opportunities and respond to challenges within their employment.</p>",,"Lord Agnew of Oulton",,"2017-10-30T17:29:25.797Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773036/answer","Biography information for Lord Agnew of Oulton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773036/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773036/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-10-18","Vocational Guidance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what steps they are taking to ensure that working people of all ages have easy access to information and guidance on the education and training they can undertake to reskill or upskill.","false","Biography information for Lord Shipley",,"Lord Shipley","HL2237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773037","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>While we have not raised this specific issue with the Israeli authorities, we remain deeply concerned about restrictions on freedom of movement within the West Bank, including Hebron. The Minister for the Middle East and North Africa visited the Old City of Hebron in August and witnessed the restrictions faced by Palestinian families and the impact on their lives. Through our Embassy in Tel Aviv we have lobbied the appropriate authorities on the issue of movement and access.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2017-11-01T15:52:15.523Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773037/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773037/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773037/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-10-18","Israel: Hebron","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what representations they have made to the government of Israel regarding restrictions placed on Palestinian families, including the welding shut of front doors of houses, in the occupied Old City of Hebron.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773038","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-27","<p>The Department for International Development's core and non-core funding to the United Nations Children’s Fund (UNICEF) in (1) 2014–15, (2) 2015–16, and (3) 2016–17 can be found in the table below. These figures are taken from ‘Statistics on International Development: gross public expenditure tables’ and DFID’s management information system.</p><p> </p><p><strong>(£ Millions)</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2016/17</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DFID core funding to UNICEF</p></td><td><p>48</p></td><td><p>48</p></td><td><p>48</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>DFID non-core funding to UNICEF</p></td><td><p>266.5</p></td><td><p>276.3</p></td><td><p>349.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total DFID funding to UNICEF</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>314.5</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>324.3</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>397.2</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The non-core figure for 2016/17 is provisional. It may be subject to minor revisions when the 2016 and 2017 Official Development Assistance (ODA) statistics are published.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-10-27T11:21:59.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773038/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773038/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773038/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-18","UNICEF: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what was the Department for International Development's core and non-core funding to UNICEF in (1) 2014–15, (2) 2015–16, and (3) 2016–17.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2239"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773039","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-27","<p>Between April 2014 and March 2017, DFID provided Marie Stopes International (MSI) with core funding to the value of £12.0 million and non-core funding to the value of £112.9 million. A breakdown of this funding by financial year is provided below.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Core funding</p></td><td><p>Non-core funding</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£4.4 million</p></td><td><p>£34.0 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£4.4 million</p></td><td><p>£41.7 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016-17</p></td><td><p>£3.3 million</p></td><td><p>£37.2 million</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Core funding was delivered through DFID’s Programme Partnership Arrangement, which supported MSI to deliver improvements in maternal health in sub-Saharan Africa and Asia.</p><p>Non-core funding supports programmes delivered by MSI. DFID support to these programmes enables women and girls to complete their education, take up better economic opportunities and have control over their own lives, therefore transforming lives, and creating more prosperous and stable societies.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2017-10-27T11:22:58.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773039/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773039/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773039/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-18","Marie Stopes International: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what core and non-core funding the Department for International Development provided to Marie Stopes International in (1) 2014–15, (2) 2015–16, and (3) 2016–17.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2240"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773040","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-25","<p>DFID reports data on expenditure against specific sector codes, including all the reproductive health care and HIV/AIDS sub-groups, annually to the OECD. These data for 2015/16 are published and publically available on the Statistics for International Development website: GPEX tables. Data for 2016/17 will be released early in 2018.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2242","2017-10-25T10:51:15.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773040/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773040/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773040/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-18","Developing Countries: HIV Infection","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much bilateral expenditure was directly targeted by the Department for International Development towards HIV and AIDS issues in (1) 2015–16, and (2) 2016–17, listed as totals and divided into subgroups (a) HIV/AIDS including sexually transmitted infection prevention, and (b) HIV/AIDS including sexually transmitted infection treatment and care.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2241"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773041","Department for International Development","false","2017-10-25","<p>DFID reports data on expenditure against specific sector codes, including all the reproductive health care and HIV/AIDS sub-groups, annually to the OECD. These data for 2015/16 are published and publically available on the Statistics for International Development website: GPEX tables. Data for 2016/17 will be released early in 2018.</p>",,"Lord Bates","HL2241","2017-10-25T10:51:15.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773041/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773041/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773041/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-10-18","Developing Countries: Health Services","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government how much bilateral expenditure was directly targeted by the Department for International Development towards reproductive health in (1) 2015–16, and (2) 2016–17, listed as totals and divided into subgroups (a) Population Policy and Administrative Management, (b) Reproductive Health Care, (c) Maternal and Neonatal Health, (d) Family Planning, and (e) Personnel Development for Population and Reproductive Health.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL2242"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773042","Attorney General","false","2017-11-01","<p>The CPS legal guidance on prosecuting racist and religious hate crime recognises the potential impact of prosecutions on Article 10 of the European Convention on Human Rights (the right to freedom of expression). The guidance recognises that not only is speech which is well-received and popular protected, but also speech which is offensive, shocking or disturbing. It is essential in a free, democratic and tolerant society that people are able to exchange views, even when offence may be caused. However, when making prosecution decisions the CPS must balance the rights of an individual to freedom of speech and expression against the duty of the state to act proportionately in the interests of public safety, to prevent disorder and crime, and to protect the rights of others.</p><p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) has agreed a shared definition of hate crime with the police in order to ensure that all relevant cases are captured as early possible. This definition is based upon the perception of the victim or any other person and is wider than the legal definition. However, in order for the CPS to bring a successful hate crime prosecution the CPS must present sufficient evidence to prove that the offence meets the definition of the crime set out in the relevant legislation.</p>",,"Lord Keen of Elie",,"2017-11-01T16:07:00.19Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773042/answer","Biography information for Lord Keen of Elie","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773042/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773042/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-10-18","Hate Crime: Prosecutions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the impact on freedom of speech of the definitions used by the Crown Prosecution Service to identify racist or religious incidents and crimes and to monitor the decisions and outcomes, as detailed in their Racist and Religious Hate Crime Prosecution Guidance.","false","Biography information for Lord Vinson",,"Lord Vinson","HL2243"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773043","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-01","<p>The ethnicity data published on the Ethnicity Facts and Figures website includes data from the Census, published official statistics, numerous Government surveys and Departments’ own administrative records.</p><p>The website includes education, health and some housing data about Gypsies and Irish Travellers. It does not currently include information about permanent and transit sites, as well as unscheduled tenure, employment, social capital, income, and crime and policing for this group.</p><p>In relation to information on Gypsies and Irish Travellers, Government collects and reports data using a number of different ethnic group classifications.</p><p>The Department of Education collects information about Travellers of Irish Heritage and Gypsy/Roma separately whereas many other departments use the 2011 ethnic group Census classification which is Gypsy, Traveller or Irish Traveller. The Government will continue to add more data and update existing data on the website.</p><p>In many cases where survey data has been collected using the 2011 ethnic group Census classification, the number of Gypsy, Traveller or Irish Travellers interviewed is very small (eg English Housing Survey and Crime Survey for England and Wales). These statistics have not been provided as they are not reliable and in some cases could potentially disclose personal information about individuals.</p>",,"Lord Young of Cookham",,"2017-11-01T17:03:59.83Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773043/answer","Biography information for Lord Young of Cookham","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773043/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773043/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Travellers: Equality","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government why, in the Race Disparity Audit published on 10 October, they have not included information on housing, including permanent and transit sites, as well as unscheduled tenure, employment, social capital, income, and crime and policing, in respect of Gypsies and Irish Travellers.","false","Biography information for Baroness Whitaker",,"Baroness Whitaker","HL2244"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773059","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-23T16:02:40.793Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773059/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773059/answer","PQ108403 v.02 (1).pdf","PQ108403 v.02 (1).pdf","UKSA response","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773059/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Employment: East Ham","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of the working population of East Ham constituency is employed in the (a) public and (b) private sector.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","108403"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773060","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-26","<p>One Public Estate started as a pilot programme in 2013. Staffing and IT costs have increased each year in line with the programme’s expansion, as detailed in the table below. Staffing and IT costs to date total £4,140,408.</p><p> </p><p>No property costs have been attributed to the programme, other than those made through the grants awarded to One Public Estate partnerships.</p><p> </p><p>‘Other expenditure’ to date totals £26,583,318. This includes grant payments to One Public Estate partnerships.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Financial Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong> Staffing and IT Costs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Other Expenditure</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>HM Treasury Awards</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013-14</strong></p></td><td><p>£191,710</p></td><td><p>£510,000</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014-15</strong></p></td><td><p>£411,998</p></td><td><p>£1,190,000</p></td><td><p>£0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015-16</strong></p></td><td><p>£738,822</p></td><td><p>£6,377,500</p></td><td><p>£6,000,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2016-17</strong></p></td><td><p>£1,886,246</p></td><td><p>£12,203,668</p></td><td><p>£13,000,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2017-18 (to date)</strong></p></td><td><p>£911,632</p></td><td><p>£6,302,150</p></td><td><p>£18,000,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total</strong></p></td><td><p>£4,140,408</p></td><td><p>£26,583,318</p></td><td><p>£37,000,000</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-26T13:05:45.27Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773060/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773060/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773060/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","One Public Estate Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8212, on the One Public Estate Programme, how much of that money has been spent on (a) staffing, (b) property, (c) IT and (d) other expenditure in each year since 2013-14.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","108426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773061","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-26","<p><strong>The overarching framework of the charging mechanism is currently in development with input from HM Treasury (HMT) and Finance colleagues across government departments. The GPA are committed to ensuring that the charging mechanism reflects the varying requirements of individual departments. This is an extensive an ongoing process as we work to transform how government property services are delivered. By its very nature the charging mechanism will be commercial in confidence and is not intended for publication but will conform to relevant HMT guidelines. When all conditions are satisfied by HMT and the shadow GPA, a public announcement will be made for the official launch of the GPA.</strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-26T13:08:14.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773061/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773061/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773061/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8207, whether the relevant HMT guidelines are in the public domain; by what criteria the charging mechanism will be tailored to individual departments; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","108427"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773062","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>Since its inception in September 2015, the GCS Knowledge &amp; Capability Unit has made 21<br>trips to Ukraine on official business. The average cost per trip has been £917.</p><p>Since its inception in September 2015, the GCS Knowledge &amp; Capability Unit has made 10<br>trips to Georgia on official business. The average cost per trip has been £974.</p><p>Since its inception in September 2015, the GCS Knowledge &amp; Capability Unit has made 3<br>trips to Montenegro on official business. The average cost per trip has been £462.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-23T14:51:45.063Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773062/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773062/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773062/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Government Communication Service: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many trips have been taken by GCS staff to (a) Georgia, (b) Montenegro and (c) Ukraine since September 2015; and what the average cost to the public purse was of each such trip.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","108439"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773063","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p><strong>This strategy is being further developed with departments as part of the wider work in our business case preparation. The GPA continues to work closely with government departments and are committed to carrying out internal assurance and audit of the evidence to support conditions, articulate potential savings to the tax payer precedent for Go-Live.</strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-14T11:47:01.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773063/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773063/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773063/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Ministry of Justice: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 12 September 2017 to Question 8273, what proportion of the potential savings referred to have accrued to the public purse; and what estimate he has made of the amount of savings still to accrue.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","108431"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773064","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-26","<p><strong>The business case for the establishment of the Government Property Agency is developed in collaboration with government departments to capture their requirements for an integrated approach to property services delivery across government. The GPA’s business case will undergo a rigorous assurance including submission for approval to HM Treasury. Publication of a business case in these circumstances would be prejudicial to the effective audit of the policy proposals included in the business case. Final policy proposals including details of the benefits likely to be realised will be published in due course in the usual manner on <a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank">gov.uk</a>. </strong></p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-26T13:07:04.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773064/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773064/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773064/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Government Departments: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 18 October 2017 to Question 8274 on Government departments: buildings, what the timetable is for completion of the business case; and what plans he has to publish it in (a) part or (b) full.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","108444"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773065","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-26","<p>A key objective of the National Cyber Security Strategy 2016-2021 is that government will provide world-leading cyber security guidance that keeps pace with the evolving threat. As the UK’s technical authority for cyber security, the National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) is the single source of cyber security advice to UK government, industry and the public. This advice is continually updated and designed to reduce the likelihood and impact of cyber attacks.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-10-26T13:09:35.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773065/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773065/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773065/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Government Departments: Cybercrime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what guidance he has issued to departments on cyber security since the Deloitte cyber attack.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108480"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773066","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>Government Wi-Fi devices and networks use industry-standard security technologies, including WPA2, in line with good security practice. Internet security is a key priority for the National Cyber Security Centre, who continuously update their advice on issues such as Wi-Fi safety, device management and browser security, and make this available on their website. Government also recommends a ‘defence in depth’ approach to security where no single control is relied upon exclusively.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","108544","2017-11-14T11:49:02.163Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773066/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773066/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773066/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Government Departments: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of Wifi-enabled devices issued to Government employees are reliant on the WPA2 standard.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108489"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773067","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-10-26","<p>A range of channels have been pursued by the Government, including direct contact US law enforcement and with Equifax US. In addition, the Government has received regular updates from Equifax. The National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC), the National Crime Agency, the Financial Conduct Authority and the Information Commissioner’s Office are assessing the impact on UK consumers and are discussing the scope of the company’s consumer notifications.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-10-26T11:29:05.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773067/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773067/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773067/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-18","Equifax","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what discussions she has had with her US counterparts on the Equifax data breach; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108521"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773068","Department for Transport","false","2017-10-26","<p>Officials have advised that this information is not held in the format requested and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The link below provides data already published on the number of driving licences held in Great Britain by age and by postcode.</p><p><a href="https://data.gov.uk/dataset/driving-licence-data" target="_blank">https://data.gov.uk/dataset/driving-licence-data</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2017-10-26T11:19:40.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773068/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773068/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773068/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-10-18","Driving: Licensing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how many people over the age of 18 hold a driving licence in each parliamentary constituency and local authority area.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","108513"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773069","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-23","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-23T16:03:59.987Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773069/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773069/answer","PQ108536 holding response (1).pdf","PQ108536 holding response (1).pdf","UKSA response","UKSA response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773069/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Personal Income","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the difference in net income between January 2007 and January 2017 is for a family with two parents in full-time work on average earnings with two children of primary school age.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","108536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773070","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-14","<p>Government Wi-Fi devices and networks use industry-standard security technologies, including WPA2, in line with good security practice. Internet security is a key priority for the National Cyber Security Centre, who continuously update their advice on issues such as Wi-Fi safety, device management and browser security, and make this available on their website. Government also recommends a ‘defence in depth’ approach to security where no single control is relied upon exclusively.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes","108489","2017-11-14T11:49:02.11Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773070/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773070/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773070/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Government Departments: WiFi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what proportion of Government departments utilise the WPA2 standard on their WiFi networks.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773071","Home Office","false","2017-10-25","<p>Her Majesty’s Passport Office would only record the address details of a UK passport holder at the point of application.</p><p>It is, therefore, not possible to confirm how many individuals hold a UK passport in any parliamentary constituency or local authority area within the UK.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-10-25T15:29:52.887Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773071/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773071/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773071/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-10-18","Passports","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what information the Government holds on the number of people over the age of 18 who own a passport in each (a) parliamentary constituency and (b) local authority area in the UK.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","108548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773072","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-26","<p>The Government notes the recommendations in WebRoots Democracy report. This is an important issue that we take seriously. We are committed to supporting our servicemen and women in exercising their democratic rights and overcoming the barriers that might prevent them from voting.</p><p>However, the introduction of electronic voting (‘e-Voting’) would raise a number of issues which would need to be considered carefully. The selection of elected representatives for Parliament is regarded as requiring the highest possible level of integrity and, at present, there are concerns that e-Voting, by any means, is not seen by many to be suitably rigorous and secure, and could be vulnerable to attack or fraud. Furthermore, the Electoral Commission in their reports on the 2007 e-Voting pilots found that it had little direct effect on increasing turnout. To provide a system over which there are doubts to part of the electorate would not be appropriate.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-26T15:23:04.093Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773072/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773072/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773072/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Elections: Armed Forces","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what assessment his Department has made of the potential merits of the recommendations of the WebRoots Democracy report, entitled Military Voting: Enhancing access to elections for the armed forces abroad, published on 1 August 2017; and what assessment he has made of the potential effectiveness of undertaking a pilot for an online voting option for UK military personnel based overseas.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","108551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773073","Cabinet Office","false","2017-11-23","<p>Deloitte notified the National Cyber Security Centre (NCSC) to a cyber incident affecting their US<br>operations in September 2017.</p><p>Based on current information, there is no indication of impact to the UK branch of the organisation,<br>which operates a separate infrastructure to their American counterparts. The NCSC are working<br>with partners to better understand the threat and identify any mitigation measures.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2017-11-23T10:17:26.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773073/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773073/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773073/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Deloitte: Hacking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, on what date the Government was made aware of the Deloitte cyber attack.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108640"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773074","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2017-12-19","<p>This was not a breach of any Government data, but a configuration error in the Pervade Software platform used by an external third party, which led to system logs from companies, including assessors of and applicants to the Cyber Essentials scheme, being exposed. There is no evidence to suggest data was extracted. Cyber Essentials is an excellent scheme and an important part of our national response to cyber threats.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The National Cyber Security Centre has ensured the relevant third parties have taken appropriate action in response. The scheme’s Accreditation Bodies are required to take appropriate security measures through contractual obligations relating to the storage of data, including using the latest version of anti-virus software. Following the incident, an independent security audit was conducted on the Pervade software, which resulted in the implementation of a number of minor recommendations. The software is regularly penetration tested.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock",,"2017-12-19T09:51:52.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773074/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773074/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773074/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2017-10-18","Data Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, following the data breach of one of the accrediting bodies for Cyber Essentials in June 2017, what measures the Government has put in place to avoid this happening again.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","108641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773075","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-26","<p>The responsibility for managing the funding for national referendums using monies from the Consolidated Fund rests with the Electoral Commission. Counting Officers are given an overall maximum recoverable amount to cover the costs of running the poll. This is based on expenditure on the previous poll, updated for current circumstances, and is aimed to support flexibility in use of the monies by Counting Officers to make it work for the particular needs of their voting area.</p><p>In reference to the overall costs of the 2016 EU Referendum, please see the following Written Statement, presented to Parliament on 23rd March 2016 by the then Parliamentary Secretary to the Cabinet Office, John Penrose MP:</p><p><a href="https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2016-03-23/debates/16032338000011/EUReferendum(CountingOfficers%E2%80%99Regulations)" target="_blank">https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/2016-03-23/debates/16032338000011/EUReferendum(CountingOfficers%E2%80%99Regulations)</a> .</p><p>The European Union Referendum (Counting Officers’ and Regional Counting Officers’ Charges) Regulations 2016 lists the maximum recoverable amounts (MRA) for the services and expenses of counting officers and regional counting officers:</p><p><a href="https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/199442/The-European-Union-Referendum-Counting-Officers-and-Regional-Counting-Officers-Charges-Regulations-2016.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/__data/assets/pdf_file/0011/199442/The-European-Union-Referendum-Counting-Officers-and-Regional-Counting-Officers-Charges-Regulations-2016.pdf</a></p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-26T13:00:11.943Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773075/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773075/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773075/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how much funding from the public purse was allocated to the 2016 EU referendum for the (a) hire of accommodation for counting votes, (b) printing of polling cards, (c) distribution of polling cards and (d) accommodation for the opening of postal votes.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","108580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773076","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-26","<p>This information is not centrally held by either the Cabinet Office or the Electoral Commission.</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-26T15:23:31.213Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773076/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773076/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773076/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","UK Membership of EU: Referendums","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many hours were worked by public servants opening postal votes for the 2016 EU referendum.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","108581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773077","Cabinet Office","false","2017-10-24","<p>The Electoral Commission publishes data on voting at elections and referendums on its website. The information can be found at https://www.electoralcommission.org.uk/our work/our-research/electoral- data/electoral-data- new</p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2017-10-24T16:00:47.823Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773077/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773077/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773077/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2017-10-18","Absent Voting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many voters in the (a) 2016 EU referendum and (b) 2017 UK General Election voted (i) at a polling station, (ii) by post and (iii) by proxy.","false","Biography information for Darren Jones","Bristol North West","Darren Jones","108582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773078","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-26","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer that I gave on 20 October 2017 to the Hon Member for Glasgow South West (107471).</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-26T11:10:54.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773078/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773078/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773078/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Revenue and Customs: Occupational Health","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 23 July 2017 to Question 5903, what the average cost to HM Revenue and Customs of a referral for occupational health advice has been in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","108591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773079","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-26","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer that I gave on 20 October 2017 to the Hon Member for Glasgow South West (107616).</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-26T11:14:53.223Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773079/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773079/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773079/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Data Protection: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what preparatory work is being undertaken by HM Revenue and Customs in respect of the General Data Protection Regulation.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","108590"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773080","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-26","<p>In line with the requirements of the Civil Service Management Code and the ACAS Code of Practice, an employee subject to formal warnings under the attendance management policy has a right of appeal at each formal decision point of the attendance management process. The HM Revenue and Customs appeals procedure is available to all employees via its intranet and clearly sets out the process and route via an impartial appeal manager.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-26T14:58:51.257Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773080/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773080/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773080/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Revenue and Customs: Disciplinary Proceedings","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 113 of the HM Revenue and Customs Annual Report and Accounts 2016-17, whether staff subject to formal warnings under the attendance management policy submit and progress appeals in accordance with the provisions set out in paragraph 4.5.15 of the Civil Service Management Code and paragraphs 26 to 29 of the ACAS Code of Practice on Disciplinary and Grievance Procedures.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","108589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773081","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-24","<p>The standardised Open Banking application programming interfaces will be implemented from early 2018.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-24T14:14:51.5Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773081/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773081/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773081/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Bank Services: Internet","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what the timetable is for the implementation of the standardised Open Banking application programming interface.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","108626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773082","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-26","<p>The government is committed to making the welfare system fair for those who pay for it as well as those who benefit from it. Families in receipt of welfare payments should face the same financial decisions as families supporting themselves solely through work. However, in recognition that some claimants are not able to make choices about the number of children in their family, the government has provided exceptions for certain groups, including in cases of kinship care.</p><p> </p><p>Data on the exceptions will be published at a future date following quality assurance.</p><p> </p><p>As with all our policies, the government will continue to keep this policy under review.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss","108448","2017-10-26T10:48:33.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773082/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773082/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773082/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Child Tax Credit: Carers","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will make an assessment of the effect of the two child tax credit limit on kinship carers who are already raising two children.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","108635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773083","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-26","<p>On 19 July 2017, the Government laid the final implementing regulations for the EU’s second Payment Services Directive. These regulations will come into force on 13 January 2018, in line with the transposition deadline.</p><p> </p><p>Until negotiations conclude and the UK leaves the EU, all existing arrangements remain in place, including the second Payment Services Directive. Upon leaving the EU, the European Union (Withdrawal) Bill will ensure that all EU law, including for the second Payment Services Directive, is retained in domestic law, providing certainty and minimising disruption to industry.</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-26T10:42:26.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773083/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773083/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773083/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Payments: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on the implementation of the Second Payment Services Directive.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","108624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773084","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-20","<p>HMRC ensures that its HR policies, procedures and practices are consistent with the regulations and conditions set out in the Civil Service Management Code.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","107615","2017-10-20T12:11:58.803Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773084/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773084/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773084/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Revenue and Customs: Personnel Management","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what role does the Civil Service Management Code play in the determination of human resources policy in HM Revenue and Customs.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","108617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773085","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-26","<p>HM Revenue and Customs ensures that its Discipline and Grievance policies, procedures and practices are consistent with the ACAS statutory Code of Practice.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-26T14:59:42.003Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773085/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773085/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773085/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Revenue and Customs: Personnel Management","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what role does the ACAS Code of Practice on Disciplinary and Grievance Procedures play in the formulation of HM Revenue and Customs' human resources policy.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","108618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773086","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-26","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer that I gave on 11 September 2017 to the Hon Member for Glasgow South West (6005).</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2017-10-26T11:13:14.67Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773086/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773086/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773086/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Revenue and Customs: Environmental Impact Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to page 46 of the HM Revenue and Customs Annual Report and Accounts 2016-17, whether HM Revenue and Customs has undertaken an environmental impact assessment of its Building our Future Programme, and in particular on staff commuting to regional centres.","false","Biography information for John McDonnell","Hayes and Harlington","John McDonnell","108619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773087","HM Treasury","false","2017-10-26","<p>The separation of fiscal and monetary policy is an important feature of the UK’s macroeconomic framework. Monetary policy is the responsibility of the independent Monetary Policy Committee (MPC) of the Bank of England, whereas the Treasury has responsibility for fiscal policy. The MPC has the primary objective, set out in law, of maintaining price stability, currently defined as an inflation target of 2 per cent, as measured by the 12 month increase in the Consumer Prices Index (CPI).</p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2017-10-26T10:43:42.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773087/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773087/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/773087/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-10-18","Fiscal Policy: Monetary Policy","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the inter-relationship between monetary and fiscal policy.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","108558"
